<methodology slug="model-evaluation">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ai</group>
    <domain>ml-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Systematic methodology for assessing LLM quality, latency, cost, and safety across offline, online A/B testing, and continuous monitoring modes using automated metrics and LLM-as-judge.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>evaluation</tag>
      <tag>llm</tag>
      <tag>metrics</tag>
      <tag>benchmarks</tag>
      <tag>llm-judge</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>ml-ops</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Model Evaluation</title>

    <summary>Systematic methodology for assessing LLM quality, latency, cost, safety, and reliability across offline (test dataset), online (A/B production traffic), and continuous monitoring modes. Always run at minimum two evaluation passes per output: automated metric + LLM-as-judge. Never report only BLEU/ROUGE for generation tasks.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Models degrade over time as production query distributions shift; benchmark scores compress differences that actually matter in production. LLM-as-judge has evaluator bias (GPT-4 prefers GPT-4 outputs, Claude prefers Claude outputs) — use multi-judge or human calibration. Evaluation results on a static test set decay; re-evaluate quarterly or after major user behavior changes.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Selecting between two or more candidate models for a production use case</item>
        <item>Before promoting a prompt change or model upgrade to production</item>
        <item>After fine-tuning, to verify quality improvement over the base model</item>
        <item>Setting up continuous monitoring with alerts when quality drifts below threshold</item>
        <item>Running A/B tests to compare a new model against current production baseline</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Task is trivial and any capable model passes — skip formal evaluation, ship</item>
        <item>No baseline exists yet — gather production data first, then evaluate against it</item>
        <item>Purely synthetic benchmarks for a highly domain-specific task — use real query samples</item>
        <item>Budget does not allow LLM-as-judge at scale — use cheaper automated metrics as a proxy first</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="automated-metrics-by-task-type">
      <p>Different task types require different evaluation approaches. Always select metrics before running experiments to avoid post-hoc p-hacking:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Select 2–3 primary metrics per task type and define success thresholds before running any evaluation.</statement>
        <rationale>Post-hoc metric selection is p-hacking. Thresholds defined after seeing results are uninformative.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Classification: Accuracy, F1, Precision, Recall; secondary: Confusion matrix</item>
        <item>Generation: BLEU, ROUGE-L, BERTScore; note: BLEU/ROUGE correlate poorly with human preference for open-ended generation</item>
        <item>QA: Exact match, Contains match, F1</item>
        <item>Code: pass@1, pass@10; secondary: Syntax validity</item>
        <item>Summarization: ROUGE-L, BERTScore, Factual consistency</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="standard-benchmarks-2025-2026">
      <p>Use benchmarks appropriate for your domain; avoid over-reporting MMLU or HumanEval scores for production comparisons — both are saturating for top models:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Knowledge/Reasoning: MMLU-Pro (harder, expert-reviewed), GPQA (validated difficulty), ARC</item>
        <item>Code: LiveCodeBench (contamination-free), SWE-bench (real GitHub issues), HumanEval+</item>
        <item>Math: MATH (competition), GSM8K (grade school)</item>
        <item>Instruction following: IFEval (verifiable constraints), MT-Bench (multi-turn)</item>
        <item>Safety: ToxiGen, BBQ (9 social categories), RealToxicityPrompts</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="benchmark-limitations">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Reporting MMLU or HumanEval as primary production quality signal.</description>
        <reason>Both benchmarks are saturating for frontier models — score differences are compressed and may not reflect production task performance. Use domain-specific test sets from real queries instead.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using the same model for both generation and LLM-as-judge evaluation.</description>
        <reason>Self-evaluation is systematically biased toward the model's own outputs. Always use a different judge model.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="llm-as-judge">
      <p>LLM-as-judge evaluation allows assessment of generation quality at scale, but requires careful attention to evaluator bias and consistency:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use multiple judge models (GPT-4 + Claude) and average scores to reduce evaluator bias; report confidence intervals, not single-point estimates.</statement>
        <rationale>GPT-4 prefers GPT-4 outputs; Claude prefers Claude outputs. Multi-judge averaging partially cancels bias. Single-point estimates hide variance that matters for production decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Choose judge model: GPT-4 or Claude Sonnet as default judges</item>
        <item>Provide clear rubrics with 0–3 or 0–5 scales per criterion</item>
        <item>Include reference answers when available</item>
        <item>Run multiple judgments per output for consistency check</item>
        <item>Calculate inter-rater agreement (Cohen's Kappa target &gt; 0.7)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="offline-evaluation-setup">
      <p>Offline evaluation on a static test set provides the first signal for model comparison. Proper dataset construction is critical:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Build your evaluation dataset from real production queries, not synthetic ones; minimum 200 samples; version it alongside model/prompt versions.</statement>
        <rationale>Synthetic datasets miss the long tail of real user behavior. Mismatched dataset versions make cross-evaluation comparisons meaningless.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Define evaluation goals: model selection, prompt optimization, or monitoring baseline</item>
        <item>Prepare test dataset: min 100 samples for significance (200+ recommended), balanced across categories, no overlap with training data</item>
        <item>Set temperature=0 for reproducibility across runs</item>
        <item>Use same prompts across all models being compared</item>
        <item>Log all inputs, outputs, token counts, and latency per sample</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="a-b-testing">
      <p>A/B testing in production provides the most reliable signal but requires careful statistical design to avoid false positives:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define success metrics and calculate required sample size before traffic splitting; run until p &lt; 0.05 and check for novelty effects.</statement>
        <rationale>Underpowered A/B tests produce false positives that lead to wrong model selection decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Define hypothesis and primary success metric before starting</item>
        <item>Calculate sample size for desired statistical power</item>
        <item>Set up 50/50 or staged rollout traffic split with full tracking</item>
        <item>Monitor guardrail metrics: errors, latency, safety scores</item>
        <item>Analyze with statistical significance (p &lt; 0.05) and segment by user type</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="production-monitoring">
      <p>Continuous monitoring detects quality drift and cost anomalies in production, but must balance signal with cost:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Sample 1–10% of production traffic for quality evaluation; run LLM-as-judge on 0.1–1%; set cost alerts at 2x baseline and page at 5x.</statement>
        <rationale>Full evaluation on 100% of production traffic is cost-prohibitive; sampling provides sufficient signal. Cost alerts catch runaway agent loops before they drain budget.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Daily: check error rates and p95 latency</item>
        <item>Weekly: review sampled outputs for quality regression</item>
        <item>Monthly: run comprehensive evaluation against baseline</item>
        <item>Quarterly: refresh test datasets to match current query distribution</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="alert-thresholds">
      <p>Alert thresholds must be tuned to production SLAs and acceptable degradation levels:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Error rate: warning &gt; 1%, critical &gt; 5%</item>
        <item>p95 latency: warning &gt; 3s, critical &gt; 10s</item>
        <item>Empty responses: warning &gt; 0.5%, critical &gt; 2%</item>
        <item>Quality score: warning &lt; 4.0/5.0, critical &lt; 3.5/5.0</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="quality-gates">
      <p>Quality gates prevent silent degradation from reaching production by enforcing minimum standards at deployment checkpoints:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Block deployment if quality drops &gt;5% on core metrics versus the production baseline.</statement>
        <rationale>Catching quality regressions in CI prevents silent degradation in production.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Before staging: all automated tests pass, quality meets threshold, latency within SLA, no safety issues</item>
        <item>Before production: staging evaluation complete, A/B positive, rollback plan documented, dashboards ready</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-specific-rules">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Evaluation agents must rate-limit concurrent LLM calls and must not cache LLM-as-judge results across prompt versions.</statement>
        <rationale>Parallel evaluation of 1000 samples at 50 concurrent calls hits API rate limits. Stale evaluations from a prior prompt version corrupt cross-version comparisons.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/llm-judge-prompt.txt" purpose="LLM-as-judge rubric prompt (accuracy, completeness, clarity, hallucination)"/>
      <template path="templates/batch-eval-runner.py" purpose="Async batch evaluation runner using Anthropic SDK"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
